Merkel's Stage
LONDON — — Facing Theresa May, the newly appointed British prime minister, is a formidable task: implementing the wishes of the British electorate — or more precisely, that of England and Wales — to "leave the EU" and managing the profound consequences of this work.
The challenge she faces dwarfs those of her recent predecessors.
But she may have the ability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate Merkel.
Like the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, everything needed to accomplish the task is in May's hands.
She is clever and tenacious, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology and is very good at exercising control, operating within her defined boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
May has won most of the battles she has been involved in and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to fully leverage it to lead the Brexit process.
The Brexit process is underway, there is no doubt about that.
Even though Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain, May has repeatedly stated that the referendum result cannot be reversed.
She has consistently said "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers all agree with her.
But Merkel has yet to define Brexit precisely.
This is a formidable task.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare your meal.
You would find it difficult to know exactly what you will be eating.
Perhaps a "Ulster fry" from Northern Ireland — eggs, bacon, sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, your feelings about various combinations might differ greatly.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some might mainly focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others might be more concerned with gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality that Leave campaigners often ignore is that the EU will not hand over its benefits to the UK for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to appease or punish the UK (though such inflammatory rhetoric, as when new Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson called for "Hitlerian imperialism," is sometimes heard).
Rather, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has political or commercial interests they are pledged to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine, based on reality, what Britain’s objectives should be in the difficult negotiations ahead regarding its relationship with the EU (and, in terms of trade, the rest of the world).
<s>Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately), the negotiation process may take years to complete.
<s>(By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is 11 years old, might be starting university!
<s>We must prioritize to prevent the negotiations from dragging out even longer.
<s>The goal, of course, is to achieve a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) into other European countries and limiting EU citizens' entry into the UK.
<s>Negotiators will need to make concessions in one area the more they gain in another.
Merkel must fully leverage the knowledge, skills, and political capital at her disposal to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation outcomes.
But even if she succeeds in her goals, she will still find that dissatisfaction is not confined to any particular segment — this is inevitable — but rather all around.
This will加剧梅政府面临的另一重大挑战：缩小因英国退欧而暴露出来的英国社会日益扩大的鸿沟。
The industrial workers in northern and central England were the driving force behind the Brexit referendum and have long felt distant from political leaders, been left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the supposed agents of globalization — the EU.
The big cities of England — particularly London — may benefit significantly from globalization, but they have received no benefits.
<s>Due to a lack of confidence in the left-wing Labour Party led by Jeremy Corbyn, many blue-collar workers ultimately fell prey to the populist Brexit promises.
"We will reverse globalization," they declared.
"We will drive out immigrants who depress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds that we send to the EU towards public services."
They promised that Brexit would bring back a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexiters could not truly deliver on these promises.
<s>Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can immigration from the EU be cut off.
<s>Any such move would only destroy British businesses.
<s>即使经济不景气导致移民下降，那些为英国脱欧投票的工人仍然可能灰心丧气地发现低报酬的工作依然低报酬，公共服务压力依然很重。
<s>This is unlikely to boost social cohesion.
<s>The Brexit referendum has already unleashed an uncontrollable populist mood storm.
Like Donald Trump's inability to improve the lot of American working-class voters, the Brexit that appears to offer so much may prove entirely futile for those who chose it.
Despite its many merits, Merkel may still struggle to overcome such challenges.
